<paragraph pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia setifera" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
<pageBreakToken pageId="102" pageNumber="103" start="start">Conostegia</pageBreakToken>
setifera
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its setose petiole adaxial surface, setose bracteoles and sessile to subsessile, spherical flower buds. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia setifera" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia setifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lasiopoda" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lasiopoda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia lasiopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the setose indument on the petioles. One way to differentiate them with infertile material is that 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lasiopoda" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lasiopoda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia lasiopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is consistently basinerved whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia setifera" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia setifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is plinerved. With fertile material they are unmistakable since 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia lasiopoda" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lasiopoda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia lasiopoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a long exserted style with a capitate stigma whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia setifera" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia setifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a large crateriform lobed stigma, and its style is not exserted. This species was reported from Panama from the specimen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Mori et al. 3850</emphasis>
(at MO and reportedly at WIS) in both 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Almeda, F" journalOrPublisher="Flora Mesoamericana" pageId="239" pageNumber="240" pagination="164 - 338" refId="B8" refString="Almeda, F, 2009. Melastomataceae. Flora Mesoamericana vol. 4: 164 - 338" title="Melastomataceae." volume="vol. 4" year="2009">Almeda (2009)</bibRefCitation>
but this specimen was also cited as 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia dentata" order="Myrtales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dentata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Conostegia dentata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in both of the latter publications. I have not been able to locate the specimen 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Mori et al. 3850</emphasis>
to confirm its identification. This species is usually encountered in the forest understory and 
<bibRefCitation author="Schnell, CE" journalOrPublisher="Harvard University" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" refId="B77" refString="Schnell, CE, 1996. The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae). Harvard University" title="The Genus Conostegia (Melastomataceae)" year="1996">Schnell (1996)</bibRefCitation>
noted that within this habitat, only well lit branches produce flowers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
